  "prompt": "What is the difference between overhanging beam and cantilever beam?",
  "response": "An overhanging beam and a cantilever beam are two types of beams used in structural engineering, each with distinct characteristics:\n\n### Overhanging Beam\nAn overhanging beam is a type of beam that extends beyond its supports on one or both ends. This means that part of the beam is not directly supported and hangs over the support. Overhanging beams can be supported at multiple points, often with one or more supports in the middle and an extension (overhang) at one or both ends.\n\n**Key Characteristics:**\n- Supported at multiple points.\n- Has at least one end extending beyond a support.\n- Can have overhangs on one or both ends.\n- Often used in bridges, balconies, and roof structures.\n\n### Cantilever Beam\nA cantilever beam is a beam that is supported only at one end, with the other end being free. The entire load of the beam is transferred to the support at the fixed end, making it a popular choice for structures where support at one end is sufficient or more practical.\n\n**Key Characteristics:**\n- Supported only at one end.\n- The other end is free and unsupported.\n- Commonly used in balconies, diving boards, and some types of bridges.\n\n### Key Differences:\n1. **Support Configuration:**\n   - **Overhanging Beam:** Supported at multiple points with one or both ends extending beyond the supports.\n   - **Cantilever Beam:** Supported only at one end, with the other end free.\n\n2. **Structural Behavior:**\n   - **Overhanging Beam:** The load is distributed among multiple supports, which can lead to a more balanced load distribution.\n   - **Cantilever Beam:** The load is concentrated at the single fixed support, which can result in higher stress at that point.\n\n3. **Applications:**\n   - **Overhanging Beam:** Often used in scenarios requiring extended structural reach, such as bridges and balconies.\n   - **Cantilever Beam:** Commonly used where support at one end is feasible and where the aesthetic or functional design benefits from an unsupported end, like in cantilevered balconies or diving boards.\n\nUnderstanding these differences helps in selecting the appropriate type of beam for specific structural requirements and applications.",
